column10: Worse if I did not understand the controls
I'm not sure, probably better due to being able to react quicker
I have never used VR before, so learning the controls and adapting to the environment would most likely make me perform worse.
I would probably be worse at first because I am unfamiliar with VR, but be more immersed after that so I would do better
column13: I've always used a controller more often, so VR would be much easier for me as long as I had that available.

From my experience going from playing a game like thumper not in VR to in VR is a very different experience, our brains can kind of trick our bodies about how they feel motion even when sitting still as long as the experience is immersive enough.

column10: I would say better as I would be in the world of tetris, so i would have nothing else to focus on other than the game.

column13: It was difficult to be immersed when the entire thing was lagging super hard the whole time.

column10: I think it would depend entirely on what the VR controls are like. If it was the same controls I don't think I would do any better. Since this is basically a 2d game I don't see how I could do better in VR. If it was 3d that would be different.
column13: I've never played tetris in VR but I have played a 3D puzzle type game in VR as well as outside of VR, and the VR environment was way more immersive and it was so much easier to use the VR controls to move around and beat the puzzle.

column10: I think I may do a little worse due to my inexperience with VR
